ties and the grim consequences of institutional racism. For this edition, Bettina Aptheker has provided an introduction that revisits crucial events of the late 1960s and early 1970s and puts Davis's case into the context of that time and our own—from the killings at Kent State and Jackson State to the politics of the prison system today. This book gives a first-hand account of the worldwide movement for Angela Davis's freedom and of her trial. It offers a unique historical perspective on the case and its continuing significance in the contemporary political landscape.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 4aGender Studies. 4aLabor History. 4aU.S. History. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / African American Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311060674440uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080147014140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801470141423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801470141/original  a978-3-11-060674-4  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK